  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Unprecedented Clean Energy Demand:</strong> Artificial Intelligence data centers require enormous amounts of carbon-free baseload power. NextEra is the best positioned company globally to supply this.</li>
    <li><strong>Florida Population Growth:</strong> The regulated utility side (FPL) benefits from continuous inward migration to Florida, ensuring steady base rate growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Cuts:</strong> The massive debt load is a burden at current rates. If the 10Y Treasury drops significantly, interest expenses will fall, boosting cash flows and lowering the discount rate.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Higher For Longer Interest Rates:</strong> A utility is a bond proxy. If rates stay elevated at or above 4-5%, the 6.0% discount rate assumption will be too low, and the intrinsic value will plummet.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Pushback:</strong> Florida Power & Light regularly requests rate increases to fund infrastructure. Any political or regulatory resistance could throttle returns.</li>
    <li><strong>Supply Chain Constraints:</strong> Building massive solar and wind installations relies on complex global supply chains (e.g., solar panels from Asia) that are subject to tariffs and geopolitical tension.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 6% discount rate? Isn't that too low?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">It is low compared to tech companies, but appropriate for regulated monopolies. Utilities have highly predictable cash flows and can handle high debt loads. A WACC calculation blending cost of debt (which is cheap) and cost of equity naturally brings the discount rate down for utilities compared to the broader market.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is Net Cash massively negative (-$92.8B)?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">NextEra has over $95 billion in total debt. This is standard for capital-intensive utilities that borrow heavily to build power plants and grid infrastructure. The DCF model deducts this massive debt pile from the Enterprise Value to find the true Equity Value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

